Delegates in C#
A delegate is like a pointer to a method. It defines a type that can reference methods with a specific signature.

They allow methods to be passed as parameters, enabling flexible callbacks and event handling.

Delegates support encapsulation of method calls, making code more reusable and dynamic.

Common uses:

Event handling (event keyword uses delegates under the hood).

Passing functions as arguments.

LINQ and anonymous methods.

Syntax:

csharp
public delegate void MyDelegate(string msg);
MyDelegate del = new MyDelegate(PrintMessage);
del("Hello World");
Variants:

Single-cast delegate → points to one method.

Multicast delegate → points to multiple methods.

Built-in delegates → Func<>, Action<>, Predicate<>.

